<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>_x000b__x000b__x000b_</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><a name="_Toc58837666"></a><a name="_Toc228955525"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from the National Outsourcing Association (LPG 21)</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">National Outsourcing Association’s (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">NOA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> contention that an entirely new approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to outsourcing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">needs to be established within the public sector to bring about significant improvements in procured services over the long term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, as well as to aid the UK economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Although outsourcing is not directly mentioned in the Committee’s call for evidence, £82bn of outsourced services are provided to the public sector each year, which we believe makes outsourcing highly relevant.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Further to that, </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">Oxford Economics in April 2011 estimated that turnover across all ‘outsourced’ markets amounts to some £207 billion per annum, equivalent to some 8.0% of economy-wide output. The private/public sector split is approx</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">imately</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt"> 60%/40%.</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt"> The UK outsourcing industry supports 3.3 million jobs and </span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">contributes £28.5 billion to the Treasury each year.</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt"> It is a significant and growing industry in the UK, yet it gets castigated more than praised, oft because it becomes the scapegoat for some other failure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The truth is ‘outsourcing works’, when done right. E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">vidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> suggests</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that outsourcing can lead to savings of between 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and 30%.  If we conservatively assume effective outsourcing delivers savings of 10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">% that amounts to a saving on £82bn of services, of £8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.2bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> per annum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">But it only works, when it’s the right solution for the given scenario and when it’s done</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt"> well</span><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It seems clear to many that the skills and culture that are required for outsourcing to work consistently well in the public sector simply do not exist.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The NOA’s recommendations are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Government should aim to act as a better educated commissioner of services.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Outsourcing and shared services contracts should, where appropriate, make budgetary provisions for suppliers to offer training and education for clients as part of the services package.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Both Government and suppliers need to educate their employees so they clearly understand the benefits of outsourcing and that they can act as partners to achieve mutually positive outcomes. (We recommend NOA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">qualifications in outsourcing strategy and practice and maintaining formal continuing professional development (CPD) in sourcing skills and practice).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Programmes must be put in place that facilitate a change in the culture, to one that values and promotes highly collaborative supplier relationships.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Clients should ensure that business objectives are clearly and simply stated from early on in the procurement process, and shared by all parties.   If business objectives change in the near to long term, the contract should give the supplier the ability to make reasonable adjustments to service delivery. </span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Early and more flexible engagement is a desirable way of aligning the interests of the supplier and the customer. Both suppliers and customers need more clarity on how they should conduct these pre-procurement conversations to mutual benefit. </span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Clients should place more importance on outcomes, rather than processes, and ensure that outcomes are always clearly stipulated in contracts. </span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Where possible, social outcomes should be articulated in contracts and the benefits of those social outcomes for the general public should be celebrated when achieved.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Government should ensure that there is a robust and effective device through which best practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> guidance can be communicated to public sector procurement teams.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Clients should standardise service specifications where possible so that other potential participants within the sector can follow a successful model. It is preferable to maximise the commonality that exists between bodies rather than demand unnecessary individual bespoke services. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is critical for newly created arm’s length bodies to review and adopt pre-existing successful service models rather than necessarily constructing their own systems from scratch. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The NOA can help through qualification and accreditation and we propose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">all public bodies review their sourcing practices against the NOA best practice Life Cycle and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">over time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">achieve and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">maintain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">accreditation for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">their practices.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> We also promote the development of shared best practice and call on Government to start voicing support for this essential and burgeoning industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">NTRODUCTION</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">National Outsourcing Association (NOA), established in the UK in 1987, is the leading independent advocate for best practice in outsourcing and related activities.  Its membership comprises of organisations that use outsource services, those that provide outsourced services and advisory organisations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> some of the largest organisations in the world including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">IBM, Wip</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ro, Cap Gemi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ni, Slaughter and May, Deloitte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, Unilever, Centrica, Astra Zeneca, EE and Aviva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This submission has been collated through work with and evidence from our members.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">For simplicity, throughout this evidence, an outsourced or shared service is defined to be a service or services supplied by a third party. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Outsourcing, particularly when it is within the public sector, attracts considerab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">le criticism.  Many hold a deep-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">seated view that public sector bodies must not contract with private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bodies to deliver public services.  Whenever there are issues relating to the delivery of a service that is provided by an outsource provider there is often widespread condemnation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of that provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are witnessing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an overriding culture that exists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which establishes and sustains a toxic relationship between the public sector and its suppliers. Recent reports of the issues relating to services delivered by Serco and by G4S do support this. The reported comments of the senior executives of the provider organisations are invariably conciliatory and suggest they are keen to resolve the issues identified. They contrast starkly with the critical, judgemental and belligerent tone of the government. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Privately the NOA has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> been told many times by public sector bodies that the culture that persists is one in which suppliers are poorly treated and there is little or no trust. It is this common relationship dynamic that leads some to suggest that the public sector is 10 years behind exemplar private sector organisations in its sourcing management maturity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Outsourcing, when delivered well, has an important role to play in the Government’s plan for deficit reduction, and can make the vital savings that Government needs. Ian Watmore, former Chief Operating Officer at the Cabinet Office, stated in November 2011, that outsourcing and shared services</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> were </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“at the heart of the efficiency and reform agenda.”</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s Dame DeAnne Julius pointed out in her 2008 report (Public Services Industry Review) this censure when things go wrong is not matched by any level of recognition when a service is delivered successfully.  She has recently reiterated her recognition of the value that outsourcing is able to provide the public sector.  In an article in the Financial Times she said, “"Using a specialist provider whose reputation and share price are on the line, commissioned and monitored by an in-house procurement team, results in higher reliability, better quality and cost savings - it is better than doing it yourself.  "It's a hat-trick too good for the public sector to pass up, especially when money is tight."  She went on to point to the findings of her 2008 review which identified savings of between 10 and 30%, with the quality of services also improving in many cases.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Although often not published there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">examples of successful outsourcing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Recently the Financial T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">imes reported (24 June 2013) that G4S has delivered 18% of savings to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Lincolnshire Police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d trimmed £5m from the budget. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The contract is worth £229m over 10 years a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> sees G4S staff undertaking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> administrative tasks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> formerly done by police </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">officers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Lincolnshire Police also say the outsourcing arrangement has helped clear a four-month backlog of files for processing firearms licences. It also claims response rates to 999 calls have improved and that faster processing of detainees has saved 1,850 hours of police officers’ time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Birmingham City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has run a joint venture with Capita to provide IT services and to operate the council's contact centre. It is reported to have delivered something in the region of £500 million of savings to date according to the accountants Grant Thornton (22/8/13 </span><a href="http://bit.ly/16W3ExZ"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://bit.ly/16W3ExZ</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ). Grant Thornton go on to suggest that savings of 15-25% have been identified.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has outsourced many of its back office activities, including licence fee collection and is a very experienced outsource user organisation.  It reports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“Our new collection contract … started in July 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">..</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> total cost savings of £220million are expected to be delivered over eight years, releasing funding to be spent on our programmes and services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DOING OUTSOURCING RIGHT</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ADDRESSING THE SKILLS DEFICIT</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A repeated criticism levelled against government outsourcing projects, particularly those at the larger end of the scale, has been that the people who commission the projects lack the commercial expertise and nous to be intelligent buyers, and the people who eventually manage or lead the project similarly lack the necessary skills to do so. This skills deficit and lack of leadership culture has been acknowledged as a key cause for failure in many projects in recent reports by the Public Administration Select Committee (PASC) on Government and IT and the National Audit Office on Shared Services. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The 2011 PASC report on Government and IT for instance found that: “</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Managing suppliers is as important as deciding who to contract with in the first place. To be able to perform both of these functions government needs the capacity to act as an intelligent customer. This involves having a small group within government with the skills to both procure and manage a contract in partnership with its suppliers. Currently the Government seems unable to strike the right balance between allowing contractors enough freedom to operate and ensuring there are appropriate controls and monitoring in-house. The Government needs to develop the skills necessary to fill this gap.”</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">According to Ian Watmore, former Chief Operating Officer at the Cabinet Office, in his evidence to the All Party Group, Government had, "…</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Either abdicated, giving it all away, or…retained an army, which has just added to cost and bureaucracy on both sides</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">." He suggested that the government needed a, "</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Smaller intelligent group that can procure and manage a contract in partnership, and hold them to account when they need to, but help them fix things when they need to as well.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">" He said that this was a difficult skill set to find, but that the current Government was "</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">buying it in</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">".</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">CapGemini drew attention to the lack of sophistication when it came to negotiating contract terms. They found that one of the blockers to a successful negotiation was when buyers concentrated on ‘price’ rather than ‘value’. They suggest that value for money measures should be built into an arrangement, and clients should maintain a value register through the life of a contract. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Skills education needs to come from somewhere and this will be a combination of intelligent recruitment from the private sector and additional training for retained staff. One way to achieve the training could be for the supplier to offer an education service as part of the package. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">TRUE PARTNERSHIP WORKING</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All outsourcing or shared services agreements are at face value a partnership between the customer, supplier and the end users. It seems that some of the projects criticised in the past suffered either from a breakdown in the existing partnership arrangements, or from the fact that the partnership was only ever in name but not in practice in the first place. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">True partnerships require shared culture and values. T</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he business objectives of both the customer and supplier need to be aligned from the outset of a contract, as they would be more difficult to align once a contract has been signed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Written evidence submitted by Fujitsu confirmed this: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“A significant factor in the overall success of the Local Government Shared Services (LGSS) endeavour has been a clear focus on the objectives and a strong alignment of all parties involved…</span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">what really makes everything work is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">the behaviour and attitude of all those involved. We have a very clear vision of what</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">we are trying to achieve and no-one runs back into their organisational silos – it’s a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">very mature relationship. It simply wouldn’t work unless it was a true partnership.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is general agreement that the best procurements have been those where the suppliers have been involved in producing and shaping the business case early on in the process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Pre-procurement was brought up as an important stage of a successful project, but it was agreed that there could be more clarity around the conduct of these conversations.  Stakeholders felt that the pre-procurement conversations could be unhelpfully overshadowed by various factors: official cultural inertia to politically driven change, oversensitivity about equitable treatment in procurements, inherited practices unjustified by commercial good </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sense, and misinterpretations or inflexible use of EU procurement rules.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">For instance, one stakeholder said that there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“...Phantom rules or urban myths about what conversations you can have before the procurement comes out which inhibits suppliers from having properly constructive conversations about what it is that the client might want to have.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> In an oral evidence session held by the group in March 2012, Phil Pavitt, CIO at HMRC, said that HMRC would really welcome more approaches by suppliers with innovative ideas. Somehow, these artificial barriers must be stormed in order to encourage the injection of transformational creativity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Trust between the supplier and the client has been cited as a key factor in a good working relationship, especially in large deals where there are many different interests at the table. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">From the supplier side, it was agreed that keeping key people from the public sector in the partnership throughout its lifetime was an important factor in ensuring trust between all parties and helping to develop meaningful relationships between all sides. Atos mentioned in their written evidence that optimum results arose when the bid team was also the delivery team – another way of keeping the key people in the relationship.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">OUTCOME-BASED SOLUTIONS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">EURIM’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(The Information Society Alliance)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> submission to PASC enquiry into the effective use of IT made the point that Government is too focused on looking for solutions elsewhere. They said that: </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">More time and money is spent hiring outside expertise (consultants) to look at new technologies than at what is being done better by other Departments and agencies using existing technology. The need is not for more spend on benchmarking, but for rewards to those who re-use what is being done elsewhere, as well as those whose solutions are copied. Those who claim their needs are unique, so they cannot reuse what is done by others, should be made to feel embarrassed.”</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Another clear way of maintaining trust throughout the lifetime of a contract is to ensure that the risks and rewards are shared equally, for example not penalising a supplier for reducing costs by reducing their income stream, perhaps instead letting both sides keep some of the savings but "spend" some with the supplier to introduce a new function or service.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">PROMOTING BEST PRACTICE</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The NOA believes that one of the factors that might contribute to inconsistency in outsourcing contracts across the public sector is an absence of formal best practice guidance. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Special Interest Groups on best practice and governance exist in the private sector, and such a group for public sector buying might also be of some value, as would a repository or online portal, perhaps hosted by the Cabinet Office, which holds best practice examples and details successful models. This could be used to encourage re-use and give public sector colleagues a forum to discuss ideas and experiences as they go through their phases of outsourcing or shared service. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is some cause for optimism.  The NOA is being asked by public sector bodies to provide training programmes on the subject of ‘understanding the supplier’.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Those organisations that are more mature in their approach to outsourcing do recognise that at the heart of effective outsourcing lies relationship management. In turn effective relation management is driven by effective governance.  The approach to governance is itself fashioned by the leadership of the organisation.  If the leadership of the organisation continues to adopt an adversarial approach to its relationship with suppliers it is certain that the relationships will at best be perfunctory.  They will deliver only the bare requirements of the contract and invariably that will be inadequate.  This is particularly true of long term and, or complex service arrangements. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Relationship Management has become a key competency for organisations that have increasingly complex and strategic important third party relationships.  It is an area on which procurement professionals have typically developed less experience.  For many procurement professionals the focus has been on the earlier pre contract and contracting stages of the sourcing life cycle.  Once the deal has been agreed it is then left by the procurement teams to project managers to transition services to the new supply arrangement and then for others to manage the relationship on-going.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">CONCLUSION</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is undeniable that outsourcing works. However, it is also undeniable that outsourcing is not a panacea and that from time to time, as is the case with any service problems can arise.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The NOA does not advocate outsourcing in all situations rather it follows the line of the current Government is encouraging a flexible sourcing approach, be that direct or through single sourcing, multi-sourcing, shared services or mutuals. This is one in which the commissioning body takes a pragmatic view of its requirements and sources services appropriately.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">But more than that, there is a further growth opportunity. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">During discussions with the members a number of delegates said they felt that the lack of skills in the UK were a contributory cause to organisations moving work away overseas. However, there may be ways that the public sector in placing outsourced, shared service or mutual contracts, could encourage skills and competencies to be developed here, stemming offshoring and even attracting companies to</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> invest in the UK as a delivery destination</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:7pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>